{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_melville_ver02/data/sn84026749/00222254048/1923102201/0104.xml":{"full_text":"22\nI ADVANCING WASHING*\nTON\u2019S INTERESTS\nWORLD TRADE\nl PROGRESS IS\nSMALL\nDepartment of Commerce Re\nports Show Lack of Stability\nFrom Political Troubles.\nBy TOM EVERRITT,\nCosmopolitan News Service.\nThe swiftly changing currents of\nbusiness in many foreign countries\nare depicted in cable messages re\nceived by the United States Depart\nment of Commerce. Some of them\nare as follows:\nAustralia: \u201cAustralian imports In\nAugust were \u00a3IBO,OOO lower than in\nJuly, and exports for the month\nwere the lowest of the year. Im\nports from the United States were\nvalued at \u00a3500,000 more in July\nthan in the preceding month. The\nwool outlook \u2018s reported as better\nthan had been expected.\u201d\nPhilippines: \u201cThe normal Sep\ntember business revival in the\nPhilippines is absent this year.\nBanks continue their pressure and\nbusiness houses remain cautious.\nSugar crop conditions are good.\nThe 1924 budget has been approved\nby the governor.\u201d\nImprovement in Spain.\nSpain: \u201cThe financial situation\nOs the Spanish government has im\nproved slightly, as indicated by re\ncently published figures. The\ndeficit for 1922-23 was less than for\nthe preceding year. Income for the\npresent fiscal year is slightly higher\n\u2022nd expenditures slightly lower than\nlast year in spite of an increase in\nMoroccan expenses. Spanish in\ndustries, except textiles and iron\nraining, are manifesting normal\nactivity.\u201d\nDenmark: \u201cDenmark has shown\nno material change during the last\nraonth. The completion of the har\nvest assures better than the av\nerage yield, and continued rela\ntively satisfactory industrial ac\ntivity is shown in low unemploy\nment figures.\u201d\nThe Netherlands: \u201cBusiness de\npression continues, although the\ntermination of passive resistance in\nthe 'Ruhr brought a slight relief to\nward the end of September. Prices\n\u2022nd stock exchange ratings show a\ndownward trend. Foreign trade is\nImproved.\u201d\nNorway: \u201cThe unimportant\nchanges that have occurred in Nor\nway during the past month show an\nunfavorable economic trend. Unem\nployment increased, the crown con\ntinued to sag, prices are rising, and\nthe harvest is predicted to be below\n\u2022verage.\nPoland: \u201cThe continued sharp\ndepreciation of the Polish mark and\nthe scarcity -of foreign exchange\nhave resulted in further trade and\nIndustrial stability, offset somewhat\nby excellent crops, enabling Poland\nto resume its position as a grain\nexporting nation.\u201d\nRumania: \u201cWhile the cereal crop\nin Rumania is generally .good, the\noutward movement of grain is slow,\nalthough special efforts have been\nmade to provide better transporta\ntion facilities. Raw cotton stocks\n\u2022re very low.\u201d\nFinland: \u201cThe August foreign\ntrade balance of Finland was favor\nable, although the export trade was\nnot so brisk, owing to reduced tim\nber shipments and weak markets for\npaper and pulp. The money market\nWas tight, but the amount of notes\nIn circulation was unchanged. The\ncrops are proving somewhat unsatis\nfactory.\"\nN. Y. Cotton Market.\nNEW YORK, Oct. 22\u2014The cotton\nmarket was firm at the opening to\nday. Prices advanced from 2 to 15\npoints on trade buying and short\ncovering in response to unfavorable\nweather reports.\nOctober opened at 29.90, up 15\npoints: December at 29.65, up 5\npoints; January at 29.15, up 2 points,\n\u2022nd March at 29.30, up 5 points.\nLiberty Bonds.\n(Furnished by W. B. Hibbs Co.)\n\u2022%s due 1947599.28\nIst 4s due 1947 97.18\n2nd 4%s due 1942 97.12\n\u2022rd 4%s due 1928 98.15\n4th 4%s due 1938 97.20\nIT. S. Treas. 4% ctfs. due \u201952. 99.04\nWhen Opportunity\nKnocks at Your Door\nSUPPOSE the big opportunity should come\nto you one day when a certam sum of\nmoney can purchase the one thing that will\nachieve your success! Have you saved enough\nmoney to do it? Or will you see the opportu\nnity drift by, because you didn\u2019t start to save\nsoon enough\nThis chance may come to you tomorrow,\nnext week, next year. But if you don\u2019t start\nsaving now, you will never be ready.\nThat\u2019s why you should inquire about our\nFirst Mortgage Notes, because others have\ngrasped their golden opportunity by having\ntheir money safely invested with us ever since\nthey had started.\nCall or Write for Detailed Information\nSwartzell, Rheem Hensey Co.\n727 15th Street N. W.\n54 Years Without Loss to an Investor\nLocal Stocks.\nSALES.\nWashington Gas 6s, *33, s3oo@\n100%.\nCapital Traction Co-, l@loo%,\nl@loo%, 10@100%, 10 @IOO%, 10\n100%.\nWashington Railway Electric,\npfd., 5@70%.\nAfter Call.\nWashington Gas Light, 2@49.\nWashington Gas 6s, *33, sloo@\n100%.\nMoney\u2014Call loans, 5 and 6 per\ncent.\nPublic Utility Ronds. Bid. Ask.\nAm. Tel. Tel. 4sl 92% 92%\nAm. \u2022Tel. Tel. \u201cfa 102\nAm. T. T. C\u2019t\u2019l Tr. ss. 97% 98\nAm. T. T. conv\u2019l 65... 116% 117\nAnacostia Potomac ss. 86 88\nAna. Pot. Guar. 55.... 86 38\nC. P. Telephone 55.... 96 96%\nC. P. Tel. of Va. 55... 93% 95\nCap. Traction R. R. ss-. 93% 94%\nCity Suburban 5s 79%\nGeorgetown Gas Ist 55.. 86\nMetropolitan R. R. 55.... 97%\nPotomac Elec. Ist 55... 96%\nPotomac Elec. Cons. 55.. 96% 97%\nPotomac Eiec. Deb. 65.. 99%\nPotomac Elec, s, 1953... 100% 101%\nPot. E. P. G-M ref. 7s. 106 107%\nWash., Alex. Mt. V. ss. 27\nWash, Alex. Mt. V. ctf. 25\nWash., Balto. A An. 55.. 70 72%\nWashington Gas 5s 93 94\nWashington Gas 65100% 100%\nWash. Ry. Elec. 45... 70% 71%\nWash. R. E. G-M 65.. 99%]\nMiscellaneous Bonds.\nD. C. Paper Mfg. 65....1 80 1.....\nRiggs Realty 5s (10ng)... 91\nRiggs Realty 5s (short).. 97\nW. M. Cold Storage 55.. 94\nWardman Park Hotel 65,. 99 100\nPublic Utility Stocks.\nAmer. Tel. Te11122%(-....\nCapital Traction 100 100%\n\u2666Washington Gas 48 49\nN. &W. SteamboAt..;.. 215 220\nWash. Ry. Elec. com.. 68% 69%\nWash. Ry