POWER\nTESTS STOCK I\nVALUES\nCousins Finds It to Be Better\nGauge Than Market or\nBook Valuations.\nBy W. S. COUSINS.\n(Copyright, 1923, by Cosmopolitan\nNews Service.)\nNEW YORK, Oct. 22.\u2014800 k val\nuation of securities is not an ac\ncurate gauge of either their real or\ntheir market values, an<\\ investors\nwho base their calculations on book\nvaluations may often be led far\nastray.\nThe book value of a common\nstock is ascertained by calculating,\nat fair market price, the actual\ntangible assets behind each share,\ntaking no account of such intangi\nble factors as good will, productive\ncapacity, etc. It involves a fair\nappraisal of plants and equipments,\ncash and securities, accounts re\nceivable, inventories, etc. It makes\nno allowance, however, for such\nchanges in industrial conditions as\nwould render the product of an in\ndustrial concern less valuable or\ndesirable or would destroy its\nmarket.\nTest Is Earning Power.\nIn the industrial world the most\nrigid test of values is the power to\nearn. A machine that can turn\nout twice the product of any other,\nthough costing but little more than\nits competitor,- is entitled to a\nhigher valuation. The rapid rise of\na speculative stock in the listed\nmarket, accompanied generally by\na flood of exaggerated statements,\nis based on expectations of higher\nearnings and larger dividends for\nholders of the stock. Often the\ndividend policy of the directors of\na corporation will determine the\npublic demand for the shares and\nthus have an important effect on\nprices.\nContracts between market values\nand book values are seen on both\nsides of the equation. Thus,\nUnited States Steel, with a book\nvalue of 257, commands a market\nof only 88, while American Tobacco\nwith book value of 61 is dealt in\ninactively at 150 and Wool worth,\nwhich can show a book valuation of\nonly 70 is much sought for on the\nstock exchange at 255 a share.\nRemington Typewriter has a book\nvaluation, according to a reliable\ncalculation, of less than $1 a share,\nbut sells actually in the stock mar\nket at 33, while Pittsburgh Coal\nwith a book value of 327, sells at\nabout 60 a share.\nOil Stocks.\n(Furnished by W. B. Hibbs Co-)\n]_BidJ Ask.\nAnglo-Am. Oil Co. new.. 14 14%\nBorne-Scrymser Col3o 140\nBuckeye Pipe Line C 0... 73 75\nChese. Mfg. Co 220 230\nContinental Oil Co 36 38\nCrescent Pipe Line C 0... 16 17\nCumberland Pipe Line... 105 107\nEureka Pipe Line 95 97\nGalena-Sig. Oil Co. com. 60 62\nGalena-Sig. Oil Co. pfd.. 108 113\nIllinois Pipe Line C 0.... 154 156\nIndiana Pipe Line C 0.... 86 88\nNational Transit Co 22 23\nN. Y. Trans. Co 94 96\nNorthern Pipe Line Co.. 101 103\nOhio Oil Co 54 55\nPrairie Oil Gas C 0.... 167 169\nPrairie Pipe Line C 0.... 99 99%\nSolar Refining Col6B 175\nSouthern Pipe Line C0..1 91 93\nSouth Penn. Oil Coll 4 117\nS. W. Penn. P. L. C 0.... 77 79\nStandard Oil Co. (Ind.).. 55% 56\nStandard OU Co. (Kan.).. 88% 39%\nStandard Oil Co. (Ky.)... 90 92\nStandard Oil Co. (Neb.). .215 225\nStandard Oil Co. (N. Y.). 41% 42\nStandard Oil Co. (Ohio).. 270 280\nSwan Finch Co 22 27\nVacuum OU Co 50 50%\nWashington OH Co. 17 23\nPenn.-Mexican Fuel 20 23\nChicago Grain Market.\nCHICAGO, Oct. 22.\u2014There was\nslight change in grain markets at\nthe opening today. Corn was lower.\nWheat started unchanged to\ncent higher, with scattered trade.\nCommission houses sold at the out\nset, but locals took hold on the\nbreak that resulted.\nCorn started to cent higher,\nwith scattered commission house\nselling on the fine weather. Trade\nlight.\nOats started to %c higher,\nwith cash houses buying December\nand offerings light.\nOpening prices here were:\nWheat December, $1.05%\n1.05%; May, $1.10%@1.10%.\nCorn\u2014December, 75@75%c; May,\n72%@72%c; July, 72%@72%c.\nCOURT FREES MARINE\nBLINDED BY DRINK\nHaving completely lost his sight\nseveral days ago after drinking a\nbootleg concoction that he bought on\nthe train while en route here, Martin\nMarshall, a marine stationed at\nQuantico, was brought to Police\nCourt today to answer charges of\nIntoxication. Judge Robert Mat\ntingly said that he thought Marshall\nhad been sufficiently punished, so\nplaced him on probation.\nMarshall was arrested upon his ar\nrival at Union Station and taken to\nthe station house, where it was\nfound that he was completely blind.\nHe was removed to Gallinger Hos\npital, where it was feared by physi\ncians that he might never regain his\nsight, but careful treatment there\nhas effected a cure and his physical\ncondition was pronounced perfect by\nattendants.\nAuto Grocers Bankrupt.\nA petition in voluntary bankruptcy\nwas filed today in the District Su\npreme Court by the Pee Kay Aut\nGrocers, Inc., which had been operxt\ning door-to-door auto trucks. The\npetition is signed by John I. Power,\nas president, and sets forth that\nthe liabilities of the company are\n$53,015.75 with assets at $33,171.86.\nAttorneys Simon, Koenigsberger A\nYoung appear for the\nNEW YORK STOCK EXCHANGE\nQuotations Received by W. B. Hibbs Co.\nI\n1:00 Sat.\nHigh Low P. M. Close\nAdv. Rumley...\nAjax Rubber.., 5% 5% 5% 5%\nAlas. Juneau... 1% 1% 1%\nAlaska G01d....\nA. Chem.A Dya. 63% 63 63 63%\nA. Agr. Chem... 12# 12% 12%\nA.Ag.Ch.pf.... 31% 3 X 31 x 32\nA. Beet Sugar.. 34 34 34\nAm. Bosch 25 36 25 25\nAm. B. Shoe.... 71% 71% 71%\nAm. Can 54% 93% 93% 93%\nAm. Chicle 11% 11% 11%\nAm. Cot. Oil pf. 19% 19% 19% 19%\nAm. In. Corp... 18% 17% 17% 18%\nAm. Meta1...45 45 45\nAm. Loco 70% 69% 69% 69%\nAm. S. A Com.. 11% 11% n% 11%\nAm. Smelting.. 66 56 56\nAm. Steel\nAm. Sugar 59 68% 68% 59\nAm. Sug. pf.... 99% 99% 99% 99\nAm. Burnt. T.., 21% 20% 20% 20%\nAm. T. A T 123% 123% 123% 123%\nAm. Tobacco... 151% 150% 150% 151\nAm.Wat.W.6s.. 61% 61% 61% 61\nAm. W. Wks. 7i 92% 90 92% 91%\nAm.W001...... 73 71% 71% 72%\nAm. Woolpf... 100% 100% 100%\nAnaconda 35% 35% 35% 35%\nArm. Co. Pr... 90 89% 90\nArnold Cons. Co 16% 15% 15% 16%\nAsso.D.Goods.. 78' 76% 78\nAtchison....96% 96% 96% 96%\nAtchiso