9% 58% 58% tB%\nTobaccopfd... 110% 1:0% 110% 111\nTob. pf. A..... t 9 88% 88% tB%\nUnion Pac 128% 128% 128% 129\nUnited F00d.... 5% 5 5 5%\nU.8.C.1.P 38% 38% 38% 38%\nU.S.lnd. A1c0... 53% 52% 52% 13\nU.S. Rub 35% 33% 33% 15%\nU. S. Rub.lst pf 85% 83 84% 86%\nU.S. Steel 88% 87% 87% tB%\nU. S. Steel pr... 119 118% 113% 118%\nVanadium Inc.. 28% 28% 28% 28%\nV. Chem.pl 25% 25% 25% 22\nVivaudou 16 16 16 15%\nWabash pf. A.. 32 31% 31%\nWh.&L. E.... 6% 6% 6% 6%\nWest. Union... 106 106 106 105%\nWestern Md.._ 8% 8% 8% 9\nWhite Oil Corp.\nWillys-Over.... 76% 6% 7\nWillys-Over. pf. 70 68% 68% 69%\nWoolworth.... 271 268 271 265\nOpen. High. Low. Close.\nMoney on call.. 4%\nAtucK sa.vs up to-\nll a.m 12 noon. la. m. 2 p.m.\n172,400 279,200\nBuna euies up to\u2014\nK n. m 12 noon. 1 p. m. 2p. no.\n1,998,000 4,665,000\nTWO MEN CHARGED WITH\nASSAULT ON POLICEMAN\nBenjamin Allen, 24 Everett street,\nand James J. Smith, 220 New Jer\nsey avenue northwest, were charged\nwith assault last night, following\ntheir arrest by Policeman H. F.\nHampton, of the Sixth precinct\nafter they had knocked him down.\nHampton had arrested the pair\nfor disorderly conduct in a store\non C street near First street north\nwest and as he started out of the\ndoor with them they began to\nget unruly, he charges. Both were\nreleased on $125 collateral, Hamp\nton was treated for bruises at the\nCasualty Hospital.\nSTOLEN AUTO FOUND,\nACCESSORIES MISSING\nSome folks will say that anyone\nwho recovers his car after it has\nbeen stolen is lucky, but Robert L.\nMoore, of 213 O street northwest, is\nof a different opinion.\nHis automobile was stolen and re\ncovered at Conduit road and Ma\ncomb street northwest. But he\ndidn\u2019t recognize it as his car.\nFive new cord tires, a battery, a\nkit of tools, a parking light and\ninotormeter had been stripped from\nthe car. They cost aboqt $175.\nSTOCKS SHOW\nSTEADY I\nTONE.\n\nDue to Accumulation of Buy\ning Orders From Saturday\nStocks Go Higher.\nBy H. J. DUIZEND.\n(Copyright. 1923, by Cosmopolitan\nNewa Service.)\nNEW YORK, Oct. 22.\u2014The favor\nable impression gained from Satur\nday\u2019s cheerful market action was\nreflected in a steady tone in the\nfirst tw\u00bb hours\u2019 trading on the\nstock exchange today. Much was\nheard of the return into the market\nof important financial interests\nwhich according to reports, had\nformed a group to exploit the over\nsold condition of the market under\nthe leadership of a prominent opera\ntor. Whether true or untrue, this\nrthnor had the effect of discourag\ning further transactions for the de\ncline, although it cannot be said\nthat much headway on the con\nstructive side was made. No doubt\nthe news of the establishment of a\nRhineland republic with all the\ngrave possibilities which such a\nmove Implied exercised a restrain\ning influence on trading.\nDue to an accumulation of buy*\nIng orders pver the week-end, in\nspired by Saturday\u2019s strong close,\nstocks were higher at the opening.\nThere was a marked absence of\nweak spots to which the financial\ncommunity had grown accustomed.\nAlthough gains were not large in\nthe general list, there were differ\nent issues, which registered ad\nvances running as high as three\npoints, including Woolworth, Sears-\nRoebuck, Hartman, Reynolds To\nbacco \u201cB,\u201d Kresge and Dupont\nde Nemours. Trading was fairly ani\nmated and conducted with a cer\ntain degree of confidence, as far as\nthe industrial group was concerned.\nPrice movements in the railroad\nlist were more or less mixed, initial\nfirmness being impaired by some\nselling in the shares of the North\nwestern carriers, especially North\nern Pacific and St. Paul preferred.\nNew Haven was also under pres\nsure, declining about a point.\nThe reactionary tendency in this\nquarter had a salutary effect on\nthe industrials in the second hour.\nGood support was forthcoming on\nall recessions, however, and the\nsteady appearance' of the market\nwas well maintained. Rubber and\ntire stocks were exception, giving\nway modrately under light pressure.\nCali money renewed at per\ncent.\nThe alarming cables from Ger\nmany found expression in the for\neign exchanges, which were gener\nally lower. Sterling, guilders and\nNorwegian kronen made fresh lows\nfor the year.\nSTATEWCITY.\nDDE TO DE\nFLOATED\nLull in Industrial Financing\nBrings Flood of Municipal\nImprovement Issues.\nBy MUNROE ROBERTS.\n(Copyright. 1923, by Cosmopolitan\nNews Service.)\nNEW YORK. Oct. 22.\u2014Municipal\nand State officials are taking ad\nvantage of the lull in industrial\nfinancing to flcat municipal bonds\nfor which the authorization was\ngiven earlier in the year.\nIn the current week, the aggre\ngate of such offerings will be\n$8,000,000, including $2,4504)00 Alle\ngheney, Pa., tunnel and highway\n4%5; Minneapolis, $6504)00 park\n4%5; State of Oregon, $1,000,000\nhighway 4%5, and South Bend, Ind.,\n$500,000 4% per cent water bonds.\nA total of $21,500,000 of State\nand municipal issues has already\nbeen advertised for competitive bids\nin November. The State of Mis\nsouri will dispose of $5,000,000 of\n4% per cent road improvement\nbonds November 1; California of\n$3,000,000 of 4% per cent highway\nbonds, November 8; Pinellas county,\nFlorida, of $2,863,000 bridge and\nhighway 5 and 5%5, November 1;\nHillsboro county, Florida, of\n$1,500,000 of 5 per cent highway\nbonds, November 16; Columbus,\nOhio, of $1,493,000 of 5 <per cent\ngeneral improvement bonds; Dade\ncounty, Florida, of $335,000 of 5%\nper cent highway improvement\nbonds.\nThe general elections in Novem\nber offer a c<mvenient opportunity\nfor taking a vote on proposed mu\nnicipal bond issues. The sanction\nor disapproval of voters can be se\ncured with little extra expense.\nNew bond proposals this year will\nexceed $2004)00,000.\nNew York State\u2019s s!\u00bb\",< \u2022\u00bb).000 for\nsoldier bonus and building will be\nvoted on. Philadelphia will vote on\na total of $71,000,000 Improvement\nissues, embracing a broad program\nof city improvement. The issuance\nof these bonds will, if authorized,\ndoubtless be spread over a number\nof years. Baltimore will ask i's.\nvoters to authorize a $10,000,000\nbonded obligation for a new police\nbuilding. Grand Rapids, Mich., plans\nto raise $5,000,000 for a sewer;\nSaginaw, Mich., seeks $4,500,000 for\nI a sewer system, Reading, Pa.,\n$2,000,000 for t-chools, and Colum\nbus. Ohio, $1,006,000 for road im\nl provement.\nAsks That Name Be Changed.\nHarry G. Cohen today petitioned\nthe District Supreme Court to change\nhis name to \u201cRitner.\u201d He is twen\nty-two years old and is employed in\nthe income tax unit of the Internal\nRevenue Bureau. The petitioner\nclaims that \u201cRitner\" Is their family\nname. Attorney L. H. David ap\nj pears for tho, young man.\nToday\u2019s Bond Market.\n(Furnished by W. B. Hibbs A Co.)\nAustrian Gov\u2019t 7* \u201943 88\nCity of Bordeaux 6a *24 79%\nGelglum Gov\u2019t 7%s' *46...... 99\nBelgium Gov\u2019t 8s *4l >lO\nRep. Qf Bolivia 8a *47 88\nCan. Pac. R\u2019way deb. 4a.... 80%\nCuba Railway 6s '52 84%\nCan. Railway 6s *3l 99%\nCan. Railway 5%s *29 101%\nRep. of Chile 8s *4l 103%\nCzecho-Slovakia 8s *sl 93%\nDanish Mu. Loan 8a A *46... 108\nDutch East Indies 5%s *53.. fl%\nDutch East Indies 6s *62.... 96%\nFrench Gov\u2019t 7%s *4l. 94%\nFrench Gov\u2019t 8a *45 99%\nFramerican Indue. 7%s *42.. 90%\nJapanese 4%5, *25 02\nCity of Lyons, *B4 80\nU. 8. of Mex. 68 (small), *45... 47%\nU. 8. of Mex. 5s (large) 108\nParis-Lyons-Med. ctfs 6a, *58.. 72\nUnit. King. Gt. Br. 5%5, *29.. 110%\nUnit. King. Gt. Br. 5%5, *37.. 100%\nMiscellaneous.\nAmerican Smeltprg 5s 1947 91%\nAmer. Smelters 6s 1947 102%\nAmer. Writing Paper 6s, *39.. 56\nBrook. Rap. Trans 7s *21.... 88\nBeU Tell of Penn. ss. 1948... 97%\nB. A O. 3%s 1925 96%\nB. A O. cv. 4%s 1933 83%\nBalto. A Ohio ss, 1995. 83%\nBalto. Ohio 6s, 1929 101%\nBethlehem Steel 5%5, 1953.... B'J\nB. AO.S. W. Div. 3%5, *25... 95%\nAnaconda Cop. 